id: pm-xy9n
title: "appendLineAtomic is not truly atomic: concurrent appends to history JSONL can interleave"
description: "appendLineAtomic opens the history JSONL file in append mode and writes a line. For single-process use with per-item locking this is safe, but the lock is per-item and the history path is also per-item, so concurrent multi-item operations (update-many) hold different locks and can interleave writes to different files without issue. However, the reindex lock is a shared lock distinct from item locks, and the background refresh worker writes to the same JSONL indirectly. If both a mutation and the background worker touch the same item's history file simultaneously (the mutation re-enqueues before the worker finishes draining), a partial line may be written."
type: Issue
status: open
priority: 3
tags[4]: "area:history","area:storage",concurrency,durability
created_at: "2026-06-07T10:03:03.472Z"
updated_at: "2026-06-07T10:16:06.694Z"
author: audit-data-agent
acceptance_criteria: "- Document the invariant explicitly: history writes are only safe when the per-item lock is held\n- Add a dev-time assertion or eslint rule that `appendHistoryEntry` is not called outside item-store mutation context\n- OR replace appendLineAtomic with a write-temp+rename atomic approach for history JSONL (safer, slightly more expensive)"
parent: pm-o2kc
risk: low
confidence: medium
body: "## Context\n\n`src/core/fs/fs-utils.ts:40-49`:\n```ts\nconst handle = await fs.open(targetPath, 'a');\ntry {\n  await handle.writeFile(`${line}\\n`, 'utf8');\n} finally { await handle.close(); }\n```\n\nNode.js `fs.writeFile` on a handle does a single `write(2)` syscall for small strings, which is atomic on POSIX for sizes under PIPE_BUF (~4KB). A full history entry JSON can exceed 4KB for items with large bodies, making the write non-atomic. The background refresh worker at `src/core/search/background-refresh.ts:248-325` holds the reindex lock but NOT the per-item lock, meaning it reads item files while a concurrent `pm update` (which holds the item lock) could have already written a new history entry mid-write.\n\nIn practice the item lock gates ALL history writes (`item-store.ts:389-534`), so the risk is low for normal mutations. The real gap is when an extension's `service_override` writes history directly.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Document the invariant explicitly: history writes are only safe when the per-item lock is held\n- [ ] Add a dev-time assertion or eslint rule that `appendHistoryEntry` is not called outside item-store mutation context\n- [ ] OR replace appendLineAtomic with a write-temp+rename atomic approach for history JSONL (safer, slightly more expensive)\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `src/core/fs/fs-utils.ts:40-49` — append open + writeFile\n- `src/core/history/history.ts:153-187` — `appendHistoryEntry` calls `appendLineAtomic`\n- `src/core/store/item-store.ts:295-345` — `prepareLockedItem` acquires the per-item lock before any history write"
